    {
      "id": "MYSbkZIRwpNClocX7iOSR",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 5781.310295585943,
      "y": -3526.3471209383606,
      "width": 22934.125,
      "height": 1085,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#c2255c",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3U",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1440422791,
      "version": 2095,
      "versionNonce": 1690548039,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784784316053,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Instead of fighting the demons, i took help from AI and instead of hints it just straight up gave the code instead which made me realise i don't truly know my hands around java yet, i am comfortable writing it myself with minimal help from the internet, but the truth stands that i don't know the JCF\ni.e the Java collections Framework which has like 5 most common data Structures used to solve the problem. Also form the solution i learnt that sorting is sometimes the right way to go forward if it makes a clear pattern emerge that makes problem easier to solve.\nthe best time complexity this problem requires is nlogn and that is dues to the heavier sorting step as after the sort this is done in a linear pass. \nNow to actually solve the problem we sort the intervals by their start indices and then we either have all the overlappable intervals right next to each other. becuase in the random given array the overlappable intervals might come before or after a certain interval in the array that would create problems and cause us\nto do multiple passes exploding our complexity to n^2 or even n^3 approximately. by sorting we are sure that the intervals are now ordered and can be merged if they satisfy the criteria by comparing the currentIntervals and the nextInterval's start and end\nif the next interval has a start that is less than or equal to the end of the current interval we merge it into the current interval and we keep on going to do so. until we find an element that is unmergable and then that new element we add to our merged List and continue the same process. by common knowledge all the overlappable intervals by sorting are place together if we\nreally find something that is not overlappable then any interval after this interval will also not overlap with the current so we make this interval our new current and continue on.",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Instead of fighting the demons, i took help from AI and instead of hints it just straight up gave the code instead which made me realise i don't truly know my hands around java yet, i am comfortable writing it myself with minimal help from the internet, but the truth stands that i don't know the JCF\ni.e the Java collections Framework which has like 5 most common data Structures used to solve the problem. Also form the solution i learnt that sorting is sometimes the right way to go forward if it makes a clear pattern emerge that makes problem easier to solve.\nthe best time complexity this problem requires is nlogn and that is dues to the heavier sorting step as after the sort this is done in a linear pass. \nNow to actually solve the problem we sort the intervals by their start indices and then we either have all the overlappable intervals right next to each other. becuase in the random given array the overlappable intervals might come before or after a certain interval in the array that would create problems and cause us\nto do multiple passes exploding our complexity to n^2 or even n^3 approximately. by sorting we are sure that the intervals are now ordered and can be merged if they satisfy the criteria by comparing the currentIntervals and the nextInterval's start and end\nif the next interval has a start that is less than or equal to the end of the current interval we merge it into the current interval and we keep on going to do so. until we find an element that is unmergable and then that new element we add to our merged List and continue the same process. by common knowledge all the overlappable intervals by sorting are place together if we\nreally find something that is not overlappable then any interval after this interval will also not overlap with the current so we make this interval our new current and continue on.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
